english:
  title: Preface to the Small Record of Flower Cultivation
  author: Kang Hee-meng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven and earth breathe forth their gentle essence, and all things come into being. Yet nothing flourishes without nurture; neglected, all things sicken. This is why the sage devotes himself to completion and support, why heaven itself does not claim sole credit for creation, nor do the transformations of nature monopolize their own power.

    When a man of great virtue emerges to meet an enlightened ruler, and unfolds the treasures long held within his breast, then benefit flows to his age, and benevolence touches all creatures. The entire realm falls within the scope of his nurturing hand, until at last heaven finds its place and all things reach maturity—a work whose depths can scarcely be spoken or described.

    But misfortune strikes when fate turns unfavorable. The Way remains locked within the heart, unmanifested. Transformation stays confined to the home, unable to spread. The great gift is withdrawn, bent and unable to extend—and so the worthy man sometimes turns to humble pursuits, seeking there the mysteries of the whole and its supreme function. This is the tragedy of the scholar. Yet from the small we may infer the great: the man of Eastern Mound loved to plant melons, the gardener Tuohe mastered the art of trees—and in perfecting their humble work, they perfected the underlying principle itself.

    My elder brother, the Master Injae, possessed complete talent and perfect virtue. All expected him to become a minister of state. Yet he never fulfilled that destiny—his great gift remained unbestowed, his excellence confined and unexpressed. Long ago he wrote the Small Record of Flower Cultivation, embedding within it a subtle meaning. The book gathers ancient methods and mingles them with observed experience, distinguishing the needs of dry and damp, explaining the techniques of planting and tending. In it lies hidden the intention of one who assists heaven's transformations—something only possible for one whose heart penetrates the ultimate Way and whose understanding touches the mysteries of nature itself.

    Flowers and plants—they possess no consciousness to feel with us, no speech to answer us. Yet their bending and rising, their straightening and curving, their unfolding splendor and sudden decay—all this lies within my hand, and nothing in nature resists. I need only honor their nature and preserve their inherent character. Had heaven granted him longer years to apply this subtle art to the transformation of an age, how much broader would his benevolence flow, how far would his benefit extend to mankind! Would he not then have done far more than merely investigate the mysteries of transformation through the small art of flower cultivation?

    Nine years after my brother passed from this world, in the spring of the year Gyeongja, I visited his old garden. It lay abandoned and unkempt, the flowers and trees withered and sparse. As I lingered there, my heart could not help but grieve. At last I recovered the manuscript of his Small Record, scattered among his papers. I have appended it to his collected works so that those who come after may know his virtue and understand his intention, and perhaps in contemplating his words, find themselves moved.
  footnotes:
    - The 'nine five' (九五) refers to the position of the emperor in classical cosmology.
    - Eastern Mound and Tuohe are legendary Chinese figures known for their mastery of cultivation—references that suggest bringing universal principles to bear on humble tasks.
    - The 'whole and its supreme function' (全體大用) is a Neo-Confucian philosophical concept referring to the totality of being and its manifestations.
    - Gyeongja (癸巳) corresponds to 1653 in the Common Era.
